ed a social outsider at choate peck preferred the fellowship of scholarly intellectuals and in their company he developed a reputation as an independent thinker and at the same time adopted idealistic political doctrines he enrolled and studied at harvard in  while studying at harvard peck polished his skills as a writer and engaged in radical acts that ended up shocking his classmates and forcing him to become the outsider once again peck wrote that his mother referred to negroes as coons and he chose to defy her and his classmates by asking a black girl to be his date at the freshman dance he dropped out of school at the end of his freshman year when his alienation from his family and the american establishment was complete peck was married to the former paula zweier for twentytwo years she was a teacher of cooking and author of the art of fine baking  and art of good cooking  paula peck died in  they had two sons charles and samuel peck was critical of both us political parties throughout his life but leaned toward a radical form of democraticsocialism he thought a utopian world was impossible and that there would always be a battle between what he called the upperdogs and underdogs he considered himself on the side of the underdogs peck was a member of numerous antiwar and civil rights organizations and spent his life as a radical journalist he assisted the war resisters league and eventually became editor of wrl news until the s he also edited the workers defense league news bulletin in the s he wrote a labor column for a paper conducted by wrl the conscientious objector beginning in  he worked at federated press and reported on union activism and joined the american newspaper guild peck worked as editor of the corelator from the ss for core beginning in  peck became news editor of win magazine a youth antiwar magazine at times he wrote articles in numerous pacifist publications such as liberation magazine labor movement sedit pecks first protest was in new york city nyc at an antinazi rally in  and his second protest was at the nyc  may day parade peck was hired as a deck boy in  and he joined in a work strike on a boat for better food during his first voyage in september  peck was on a boat that anchored in pensacola florida where peck joined the longshoremen who were on strike peck claimed the union hall was fully integrated at the time by the striking longshoremen peck remained there for two weeks before police arrested him for distributing rankandfile literature on a boat marking his first arrest in the labor movement in the s he helped found what later became the national maritime union joseph curran led a strike aboard a ship in march  anchored in nyc peck picketed with the longshoremen for the first time on march   he then picketed again from november  to january  curran led the fight against joe ryan this led to the formation of the nmu the strongest east coast longshoremen union peck would later criticize joseph currans transformation once in power of the nmu on may   peck was arrested for the second time in his life police clashed with striking seamen that day with peck being beaten and arrested this marked pecks first mass arrest as one of  strikers arrested that day that night they were arraigned making it the largest group every arraigned at the same time in that courtroom wwii resistanceedit during world war ii he was a conscientious objector and an antiwar activist and consequently spent three years in jail at danbury correctional institution in connecticut – while in prison he helped start a work strike that eventually led to the desegregation of the mess hall also during this time he participated as did many other conscientious objectors in medical experiments especially a yellow jaundice experiment which permanently damaged his liver peck viewed it as volunteering to help discover a cure for the disease and for humanity wwii amnesty movementedit peck was released from danbury prison in  and immediately joined protests to grant amnesty to wwii conscientious objectors cos peck worked with the amnesty committee in organizing protests and writing press releases peck took part in the first amnesty protest at the white house on october   peck picketed outside danbury prison on february   demanding amnesty while prisoners were on strike inside on may   peck joined the largest amnesty protest until then of  people at the white house while co prisoners carried out hunger strikes on december   peck was one of  activists outside the white house who managed to get press attention because they all wore blackandwhite prison outfits to represent wwii cos remaining in prison peck attended another theatrical amnesty rally in june  a small group staged a mock funeral in front of the white house pallbearers dressed in formal attire and carried a coffin marked justice peck joined  amnesty demonstrators on september   at the nyc station for the freedom train  a patriotic train filled with us declarations and documents that ran through  states in two years beginning in  demonstrators once again wore prison outfits which gained the attention of thousands of bystanders and reporters at the station police ordered them to move but  activists including peck refused to move and were arrested those arrested won in court and years later the police chief was ordered to issue a public apology peck once again joined  activists outside the white house on christmas day  two days after president truman granted amnesty on solely religious grounds to  cos out of more than  this meant pecks sentence was not removed from his record peck wrote in a letter to the editor in the new york times in january  stating  other countries granted amnesty to all wwii cos and the refusal to do so by the us seriously belies our professions of democracy wwii amnesty protests continued into the s but without successfully changing any laws on december   peck led a picket of  people wearing his uncle sam outfit demanding a christmas amnesty antidraft sedit peck and a small handful of wwii cos led the protests against the military draft in the s peck was among nine activists arrested on march   for picketing outside a dc hotel that hosted a dinner for un security council delegates peck handed out literature encouraging people not to sign up for military service in  president truman introduced a peacetime draft in congress which peck protested peck worked with bayard rustin and aj muste to organize a nationwide protest against the draft on february   more than  demonstrators burnt their draft cards in more than  states peck led the most popular action that day when  people burned their draft cards at the white house without any arrests peck worked with a philip randolph a black union leader after president truman proposed the universal military training act umt which continued segregation in the military in april  the wrl assigned peck to head the committee on publicity which was tasked with printing letters of support for randolphs call of nonviolent resistance to the draft the peacetime draft passed on june   but continued protests by randolph and pacifists led to truman passing executive order  which abolished segregation in the military this brought an end to peck working with randolph on june   peck joined  demonstrators in a creative picket outside the white house against umt peck and seven other demonstrators wore red white and blue uncle sam outfits as they goosestepped in circles after the passage of umt peck took on an individual protest at the white house on june   peck entered the white house in a public tour and quickly chained himself to a banister and then removed his jacket to reveal a shirt with the handpainted slogan veto the draft this became one of his most famous protests at the time and it garnered the attention of most news stations he was interrogated as being a communist after being removed but was let go without charges protests broke out in several cities on august   the first day to register for the peacetime draft peck joined bayard rustin at a rally in nyc without arrests peck and rustin were arrested however on september   at an antidraft picket in nyc both peck and rustin received  days in rikers island after the judge yelled racial slurs at rustin peck protested outside a nyc courthouse on october   in support of stuart perkoff who was the first person in nyc to defy the selective service act but two weeks later perkoff changed his mind fearing a long sentence peck supported the world citizens movement headed by garry davis who objected to conscription and war wwii cos supported davis when he was in court in france in october  october  was announced as an international pacifist day of solidarity and peck was one of a dozen activists arrested for protesting at the french embassy in dc on april   peck was assaulted by two american legion members at the third annual loyalty day parade in nyc for passing out pacifist literature he did not press charges on july   peck traveled to the un assembly at lake success where it was discussed if the us should enter the korean war peck and three other pacifists passed out literature against the war and peck made it into the building without being noticed peck found himself at the delegates entrance door and entered when the meeting began he passed out his literature to most delegates before security realized what he was doing peck was carried out of the room by security which gained the attention of most newspapers and he was released without charges antinuclear movementedit in  peck was arrested in new york city for being involved in the first nonviolent direct action against nuclear tests on july   peck and  demonstrators pulled around a stuffed goat rented from a taxidermist in new york city representing the actual goats left on the marshall islands where the us conducted the bikini atom bomb experiment that day peck was arrested that day and received a  fine a few weeks later peck and a similar size group marched from the pentagon down pennsylvania avenue and were arrested for marching without a permit peck and a small group of pacifists protested at the nyc easter parade on may   passing out antinuclear literature peck and nine other activists were arrested while marching along the side of the parade peck refused to pay the  fine and served  days in rikers island peck also marched in the easter parade against nuclear weapons on april   along with eight other activists police ordered the group to disperse but peck and mat kauten refused and were both arrested peck was carried to the police squad by four cops and his arrest landed in the new york times peck served five days in jail peck was arrested again at the easter parade with three other people in  in april  peck joined the peace vigil at the maryland aec to protest the hydrogen bomb peck was briefly arrested for passing out literature in nyc during an air raid drill on september   but was released with no charges in  and  he was arrested for refusing to take cover during the simulated air raid drills in nyc which were brought to an end in the early s due to massive civil disobedience on june   peck was one of  people arrested for standing in new york city hall park during the first major protest against the nationwide air raid drills peck was arrested with other pacifists such as aj muste bayard rustin and ralph digia as well as catholic worker members dorothy day and ammon hennacy peck was arrested again with  other people in washington square park on july   during the second major protest against the air raid drills he was arrested again with dorothy day and ammon hennacy but was also joined by george willoughby and quaker robert gilmore who later became a leader for the antinuclear organization sane in may  peck refused to take shelter during the nyc air raid drill along with  other persons marking the largest act of civil disobedience against the program in  peck was one of the founding members of the new organization nonviolent action against nuclear weapons one of the leading antinuclear groups at that time peck was arrested with ten others at the organizations first event on august   for performing civil disobedience at the nuclear test site in nevada beginning in  peck took part in the large walk for peace campaigns conducted internationally and became involved in the golden rule campaign the golden rule was a foot ketch that set sail into the nuclear testing sites in the pacific ocean as an act of protest peck was not part of the initial crew but he did participate in a weeklong fast inside an aec building with roughly a dozen other persons in support of the golden rule in june however peck filled an open spot on the golden rule and was arrested with the crew six miles off the shore of honolulu the entire crew served  days in jail peck became one of the most famous antinuclear activists in the country following the golden rule campaign and he traveled to the geneva conference that fall to advocate for a mutual test ban treaty between the us and soviet union on june   when peck was picketing nuclear bases in new london he was attacked by a mob of workers who destroyed his placard when the soviet union resumed nuclear tests in august  peck was part of a delegation that delivered a peace statement to the soviet embassy peck returned to the soviet embassy on october  with  demonstrators and he was once again part of the delegation that delivered the peace declaration in  peck was directly involved in the growing antinuclear movement on january  he and  other persons demonstrated outside an aec building in new york on march  peck was one of  demonstrators arrested near times square after police violently attacked nonviolent antinuclear activists on april  peck was involved in the massive easter protest of  demonstrators in nyc and was quoted in the new york times the next day about the need for direct action on may  more than  persons protested nuclear tests at the un in nyc and peck led one of the delegations to the british embassy where he performed a sitdown in october peck joined over  demonstrators in protesting against nuclear war in nyc which was the largest antinuclear rally up until then then on easter in  peck was a guest speaker for the rally in detroit that gathered over a thousand demonstrators when the testban treaty was signed by the us and ussr in  peck claimed the credit was due to the nonviolent direct actions over the past decade throughout the antinuclear campaign peck opposed the use of nuclear weapons by all nations and he chanted the popular pacifist slogan no tests – east or west” in october  when china conducted its first nuclear test peck took part in the first american protest against chinas use of nuclear weapons after the signing of the testban treaty however the antinuclear movement was overshadowed by the antiwar movement and didnt gain momentum again until the s civil rights movement ssedit after the war he became a radical journalist and joined the congress of racial equality core in  where he worked as the publicity officer and later as the editor for the corelator peck worked for core one of the main civil rights organizations in the north during the s from  before he was removed when the organization ousted white leaders throughout the s core was a tiny organization with only a handful of members providing peck the opportunity to take a leading role in the organization as the head editor until core grew dramatically in the s peck was arrested with bayard rustin in durham north carolina during the journey of reconciliation in april  which was an interstate integrated bus journey through the south and acted as a precursor to the later freedom rides of  in chapel hill north carolina during the journey peck was attacked by an angry white mob with one mob member punching him in the side of the head but peck remained nonviolent and safely walked away peck was arrested a second time during the journey for sitting in an integrated fashion on the bus in asheville north carolina in the summer of  peck was beaten and arrested two times during a core campaign that aimed to integrate palisades park in new jersey which directly led to the passage of the new jersey  freeman bill he was first arrested with six other people on august   for picketing in front of the pool ticket booth then on august   peck was one of  people were arrested outside palisades park and he claimed a police officer knocked him unconscious throughout the s peck endorsed martin luther king jrs montgomery campaign while debating roy wilkins of the naacp about how direct action was just as critically needed as legal procedures in winning civil rights during the southern sitin movement in  peck and other core members performed weekly pickets outside woolworth stores for  months straight in nyc peck was also the leading civil rights activist in the proxies campaign a method where peck protested segregated businesses stockholder meetings from  peck attended the stockholder meetings for greyhound company usually holding one share of stock in the company or representing others who held stock he was joined by bayard rustin a few times and core members protested outside the building during the meetings from the floor peck argued that the company should enforce integration in the south similarly he attended grants  stockholder meeting where he successfully convinced business owners to desegregate their chains in baltimore maryland in  peck used this same formula to protest the stockholder meetings for woolworths grants and kress as well as protesting mccrorys meeting in april  the proxies campaign was later popularized by saul alinsky although he didnt perform such actions until the lates freedom ride  civil rights ssedit peck and  other volunteers traveled south in  in the famous freedom rides peck was arrested on may  in winnsboro south carolina for sitting in an integrated fashion at a lunch counter on may  peck was on the second trailways bus leaving atlanta georgia for birmingham alabama the first bus a greyhound left an hour earlier and was burned in a firebombing in anniston alabama seriously injuring the passengers an hour later the trailways bus pulled in at the terminal in anniston and eight klansmen boarded and assaulted the freedom riders peck a frail middleaged man at the time was severely injured in the beating and required fifty stitches later in birmingham peck and charles person a black student from atlanta were the first to descend from the bus into a crowd of klansmen who with the organizational help of birmingham public safety commissioner bull connor were waiting for the freedom riders howard k smith reporting onthescene for cbs described the ensuing violence on the radio in words cited by john lewis in his autobiography walking with the wind toughs grabbed the passengers into alleys and corridors pounding them with pipes with key rings and with fists one passenger was knocked down at my feet by twelve of the hoodlums and his face was beaten and kicked until it was a bloody pulp lewis adds that was jim pecks face peck was severely beaten and needed  stitches to his head  peck was taken to carraway methodist medical center a segregated hospital which refused to treat him he was later treated at jefferson hillman hospital the freedom ride was pecks most famous action resulting in him gaining popularity as a white civil rights hero he traveled around the nation representing core in speeches and gained even more attention for the movement on june  when he confronted former president truman about his recent remarks denouncing the freedom riders making truman seem behind the times in racial justice at pecks suggestion a route  freedom ride project was launched by core in december  resulting in half the restaurants desegregating along route  in baltimore peck was arrested along with  others after attempting to integrate a restaurant in may  after he published his famous book freedom ride peck was one of the main leaders for the project baltimore campaign which led to more restaurants desegregating that summer peck was one of the leaders for the freedom highways campaign which sought to integrate highway restaurants in north carolina following the freedom rides peck became good friends with william lewis moore a white civil rights worker who became a martyr for the movement after he was shot and killed in the south during his solo freedom march in the spring of  when moore was killed peck delivered the eulogy at his funeral and then gave the opening speech on may  when several dozen activists continued the march from where moore was shot down after the walkers were arrested and taken to jail peck and others marched to the jail singing freedom songs on august   peck was one of  people arrested for performing a sitdown in the street while protesting the discriminatory state policies for the construction of the downstate medical center in brooklyn on october  peck spoke about the racist policies in front of  demonstrators at a nyc rally on august   peck proudly represented core at the march on washington for jobs and freedom which over  persons attended on december  peck traveled to the newest levittown in bowie maryland to picket the discriminatory housing policies on april   peck was one of the leaders for cores campaign at the opening day of new yorks world fair protesting the discriminatory policies held by most companies sponsoring the fair more than  demonstrators were arrested on the fairs opening day including peck core leader james farmer bayard rustin and michael harrington in march  peck represented core at the historic march from selma to montgomery concluding with  demonstrators entering montgomery on march  peck even had the honor to speak as a core representative that day honoring william moore in his speech when peck returned home after the march he was removed from core after working there for  years because he was white peck denounced the decision as reverseracism and never accepted the slogan of black power after he was removed from core peck personally funded kings campaigns especially his  poor peoples campaign a year after being removed from core peck took part in the march against fear in june  during this campaign the slogan black power arose which peck bitterly denounced at a concert held one night during the march peck wrote king a letter statingi wanted to assure you that despite the dirty deal i have received from core i am still with the movement and shall be as long as i live” when king was assassinated in april  peck honored him by traveling to memphis on april  to join  other demonstrators in marching in support of the memphis sanitation strike that king had supported prior to his death after the memphis march peck traveled to atlanta for kings funeral which concluded with  demonstrators marching over four miles in may  peck joined coretta king and ralph abernathy in charleston south carolina to support black nurses on strike peck continued civil rights activism into the s on march   he joined  people in selma alabama to commemorate the tenyear anniversary of bloody sunday peck also joined the controversial school bus integration protests on december   peck joined  people marching to the boston common to end the racist attacks on school busing peck returned to boston on in may  when he joined  people in a large naacp march on april   peck joined  people in dc to protest the reverse discrimination bakke case then before the supreme court vietnam waredit he continued his activism by demonstrating against the vietnam war peck began demonstrating against the vietnam war in  through the wrlinitiated committee of public conscience and the crisis subcommittee which quickly organized demonstrations in crisis situations in october  he helped launch the weekly times square vigil against the war which he participated in nearly every week for   years from oct january  between  and  peck attended every major rally in washington dc and was arrested  times for protesting the war on february   demonstrations against the war occurred in  cities nationwide and in nyc peck was one of  people arrested for performing a sitdown at the us mission to the un on august   peck was one of  demonstrators arrested outside the white house during the assembly of unrepresented people for taking part in a massive sitin against the war marking the largest amount of arrests at the white house up to that time starting in october  peck took part in the massive new york demonstrations coordinated by the single largest city coalition  the fifth avenue vietnam peace parade committee  which organized the nations largest demonstrations on international days of peace and peck openly advocated for coalition building along with civil disobedience in november  peck joined  demonstrators in dc for a rally organized by sane in  he signed two tax resistance declarations and began advising young people to avoid the draft on february   peck attended a dinner that honored president johnson with a peace award at the wardolfastoria hotel in new york city peck painted on the front and back of his shirt peace in vietnam but was covered by his coat when johnson was about begin his speech peck took off his coat stood on his chair and yelled mr president peace in vietnam he was dragged out of the room but he managed to announce his plea three more times and later served  days in jail in april  peck marched with hundreds of thousands of people in nyc as martin luther king jr led the antiwar rally on april  peck attempted to crash the  montreal expo by performing a sitin on stage to protest the war but he failed in his attempt to get arrested in october  peck took part in the famous stop the draft week as a speaker in nyc who introduced draftcard burner david miller on stage while also demonstrating in support of hundreds of youths as they burned their draft cards on october  peck was one of  demonstrators arrested for performing civil disobedience at the famous march on the pentagon in jail that night he spoke with fellow inmates linguist noam chomsky and author norman mailer peck appeared in mailers  awardwinning book on the protest the armies of the night history as a novel the novel as a history on december  during the second stop the draft week peck was arrested along with  other demonstrators outside an induction center in nyc he was arrested along with drbenjamin spock and poet allen ginsberg in  peck briefly joined students during their takeover of columbia university and he was gassed and clubbed at the notorious beatings during the democratic convention in chicago in  peck spoke out against burning draft files but still supported those arrested for doing so he was arrested on august   outside the office of the secretary of defense for reading antiwar quotations for this he was one of four people arrested along with wrl members edward gottlieb and bent anderson as well as barbara reynolds peck took part in the massive moratorium demonstrations on october  and november  which gathered hundreds of thousands of persons on march   peck was one of  demonstrators arrested for obstructing government operations at manhattans armed forces examining  entrance station during nationwide decentralized protests against the war peck was arrested that day along with draft file burner jerry elmer who later recorded the arrest in his book felon for peace the memoir of a vietnamera draft resister on april   peck joined the massive march on washington that over  persons took part in on may  the first day of the may day demonstrations in dc peck was arrested along with  demonstrators in the single largest mass arrest in history ending with over  arrested between may  and may  on october  he was arrested at the evict nixon protest in washington dc along with nearly  persons he was arrested again outside the white house with  other demonstrators on november  during the twoweek daily death toll demonstrations where activists performed dieins to dramatize the continuation of vietnamese deaths from american bombing peck was arrested again in dc on april   for performing a sitdown that resulted in  arrests on may  peck was among  demonstrators arrested for performing civil disobedience during the peoples blockade at the pentagon on june  peck was arrested in new jersey with  other demonstrators for being involved in the peoples blockade campaign that was conducted at navy ship yards to prevent ammunition from being sent to vietnam in august  peck was injured by a tear gas canister hitting him above the eye and was hospitalized during an antiwar rally in miami at the republican national convention on october   peck was one of a dozen persons arrested at the un for setting up a tiger cage replica protesting the mistreatment of vietnamese political prisoners by usbacked forces beginning in  peck became involved in the amnesty campaign that aimed to protect the rights of deserters and cos during the war on march   peck was one of  demonstrators arrested for performing sitdowns during a tour of the white house in protest against president fords conservative amnesty plan this marked the largest arrest on white house grounds up to that time peck attended the last major antiwar rally in new york city on may   when more than  people filled up central park antinuclear movement ssedit following the vietnam demonstrations in the s there was a revival in the antinuclear movement which peck took a major part in in  and  peck was part of several smaller demonstrations against nuclear testing by france in  and  he joined japanese delegates in nyc in protesting nuclear weapons then in  he attended the first two organized demonstrations against the government’s first strike nuclear policy throughout  peck was heavily involved in the continental walk for disarmament and social justice a ninemonth march with  routes covering  states peck joined the southern leg of the march that launched from new orleans on april  the southern leg members consisting mostly of japanese monks and poor blacks were arrested six different times while marching through the south but peck was only present and arrested at four of these birmingham alabama rocky mount nc new bern nc and ahoskie nc the last day of the continental walk for disarmament and social justice was in washington dc on october  attended by  persons peck joined the procession of death to the pentagon where he and  other persons were arrested for laying coffins on the steps of the building on october  and november   peck joined in protesting chinas resumption of nuclear tests in the summer of  peck and american poet millen brand traveled to japan and joined the march from nagasaki to hiroshima the most famous feeder route of the thirteen involved in the japanese peace walk peck and brand attended numerous meetings with a variety of groups spoke with government officials and were the leading speakers at every event for the day march when peck returned home from the japanese walk he shared his experiences in a tour through the us sponsored by the wrl and the mobilization for survival one of the largest coalitions of antinuclear groups his tour concluded in colorado where he joined a meeting hosted by rocky flats national action committee rfnac an antinuclear group opposed to the major nuclear bomb plant in rocky flats co at the meeting peck was the first outofstate person to endorse the rfnacs rally at rocky flats for april   peck was one of  persons demonstrating at rocky flats and after the rally he was one of  persons who launched a hour sitdown on the railroad tracks leading to the plant although peck was only on the tracks for the first day the sitdown was sustained for several months peck returned to rocky flats for a second major rally on august  where he sang a japanese peace song he learned during the japanese walk on august  he was one of  persons to perform a diein along with allen ginsberg and daniel ellsberg at the rocky flats plant resulting in all of them being arrested he returned to rocky flats again on april   along with  demonstrators and he joined the sitdown on the tracks with  others for which he was arrested for during the special session on disarmament at the united nations in nyc in the spring of  peck joined in the major actions launched by the mobilization for survival on may  peck joined over  demonstrators in a march on the un and on june  he was arrested along with  other demonstrators at the us mission to the un for employing civil disobedience during the sitin for survival one of the largest mass arrests in nyc history later that month he demonstrated for the third time at the notorious seabrook plant in new hampshire on october  the opening day of the arms bazzar in washington peck joined a picket line to protest the manufacturing of military weapons on february   during the trial of the white house  peck held up a giant banner in court that read “no nuclear weaponsno nuclear power usa or ussr he then led a march to the white house where he was one of  persons arrested for performing a sitdown when the nearmeltdown almost occurred at three mile island in march the antinuclear movement expanded dramatically only two days later when peck marched in an antinuclear demonstration in nyc he was amazed that a thousand bystanders joined in the pouring rain on april  he marched with over a thousand persons in a protest to shut down the consolidated edison’s indian point nuclear reactor on may  peck participated in the massive washington demonstration that over  persons participated in led by ralph nader then on june   over  major demonstrations took place across the country as part of europes international days of protest peck was one of  people arrested that day for occupying the site at shoreham on long island after the largest rally that day was attended by  a major antinuclear concert was held in september for several days with performances by legendary bands such as tom petty and bruce springstein on september  peck joined over  persons in manhattan for the concluding rally marking one of the largest antinuclear rallies up to that time peck found one of the most significant actions to be the wall street action on october  the th anniversary of the stock market crash since it brought the fight to the financiers of the nuclear industry that day peck was one of  demonstrators to be arrested along with david dellinger and daniel ellsberg for attempting to block the entrances of the stock market exchange building on april   peck marched with  demonstrators to the pentagon where he and nearly  others were arrested for blocking the entrances of the building including daniel ellsberg dr benjamin spock david mcreynolds and grace paley peck also took part in the largest antinuclear rally held in nyc on june   with one million people in attendance it marked the single largest demonstration in the country for any cause the rally marked the peak of antinuclear movement and led to dramatic changes in the political realm following the largest rally in history a massive civil disobedience campaign was set for june  at the un that day over  persons were arrested for blocking the entrances of the five nations possessing nuclear weapons making it the single largest arrest in the citys history peck was part of the first group arrested that day outside the us mission to the un this was possibly pecks last arrest in his life having been arrested nearly  times overall prison movement sedit the prison movement stemming from the radical protests of the s was crystallized by the attica prison riot in september  which ended with ny officials sending in reinforcements to crush the riot resulting in dozens of deaths in memory of the deaths from attica protests were held at nearly  prisons nationwide on october   peck attended the largest protest that day at danbury connecticut prison where he was held during wwii peck rallied with  people at kenosia park before hundreds rallied at the prison peck joined a thousand people on october   protesting an award dinner for governor rockefeller who was responsible for the decision to move in on attica prison a wave of prison strikes swept the nation in  prisoners at danbury prison went on strike due to poor working conditions and slave wages on march   peck joined activists in picketing outside danbury prison on october   peck joined  people outside cooper union to protest gov rockefellers planned speech over his orders during the attica riot peck criticized the young people at the rally who later broke the windows at chase manhattan bank which became a big part of the story the following day in the new york post peck reveled the popculture of the prison movement found in movies and books peck wrote a review in win magazine in  covering leon dashs book the shame of the prisons he also enjoyed the  publication of an eye for an eye and the  book danbury anatomy of a prison strike because it showed how the vietnam protests were intertwined in the prison strikes peck wrote in the  win magazine that his two favorite prison plays were the jail and attica peck became involved in the case of former boxer rubin hurricane carter who was sentenced to prison in the s after reading his famous  book the sixteenth round from number  contender to number  on february   peck joined a march from trenton nj state house to the trenton prison in support of carter hosted by the nj workers committee against police repression death penalty movement sedit from  to  the us had a de facto moratorium on capital punishment but in  it became legal again after gregg v georgia peck took part in one of the dozen southern vigils held on christmas eve  against the death penalty peck joined the candlelight vigil in new orleans one of the dozen cities to hold vigils orchestrated by the southern coalition on jail  prisons peck joined the national easter witness against executions protests in april  organized by the southern coalition on jail  prisons on april  peck marched with  activists in atlanta georgia to end the death penalty and protect the dawson  on april  peck attended a similar rally in new york city where he heard famedactivist attorney william kuntsler on march   peck protested north carolina governor james hunt at a new york city symphony orchestra because the governor refused to intervene in the notorious international case of the wilmington  on march   peck joined  people in a march on the white house to free the wilmington  on april   peck joined a night vigil against the scheduled alabama execution of john louis evans which ended in celebration when the judge granted a last minute reprieve on august   peck was one of  demonstrators arrested for violating a court order by attempting to cross a bridge in reidsville georgia in order to reach georgia state prison on the other side peck was arrested there along with dick gregory to show support for the reidsville six who were accused of starting a prison riot the year before on november   peck was one of  persons arrested at a protest against capital punishment at the supreme court building in dc sponsored by people against execution pax the rally was called florida day to represent the more than  prisoners facing the death penalty in the state a series of mock executions were conducted upon the  people risking arrest who sat in a handmade electric chair and pretended to be executed the  bodies were carried across the street and placed on the steps of the supreme court where they performed dieins until their arrests labor sedit peck continued his s labor activism in the s on october   he protested alongside a dozen asianamerican organizations against employment discrimination outside the headquarters for the international ladies garment workers union for posting advertisements along the idea that japan threatened american jobs peck openly supported more radical rankandfile unions because they could win victories in wildcat strikes but he protested what he considered to be a more conservative union the united steelworkers peck joined  people in protesting the united steelworkers convention in atlantic city nj on september   over the unions experimental negotiating agreement with us steel corporation which prohibited any type of strike peck took part in the first international demonstration against multinational corporations on earth day march   launched by coalition against global enterprises cage half a dozen protests were held within the us and protests were held internationally in brussels norway stockholm and tokyo peck protested in nyc outside itt building where he held signs quoting anthony sampsons  book the sovereign state of itt on june   peck went to what he said was the largest wall street protest he attended up to that time of  union demonstrators the municipal labor committee representing the major municipal unions organized the rally against the  crisis budget proposed by the mayor of new york city which threatened thousands of municipal jobs the demonstration was associated with an economic attack by the union which threatened to withdraw millions of dollars from first city national bank if the crisis budget went through peck protested jp stevens in the s an antiunion company that paid significantly lower wages than most factory jobs on september   four men were arrested inside a jp stevens store for standing in front of scab products and wearing shirts that read boycott jp stevens this was noted as the first tin on november  another dozen people including peck and david mcreynolds were arrested inside the nyc jp stevens pecks group had all their charges dropped december  by the early s peck considered cesar chavez of the united farm workers ufw to be one of the greatest leaders in nonviolent resistance peck joined weekly pickets for six years in support of ufws grape and lettuce boycotts peck met caesar chavez and spoke with him at length in may  during a mass march from baltimore to dc to protest the pentagons purchases of scab grapes to export to troops in vietnam the baltimoretowashington march marked the first one of its kind on the east coast peck traveled to pacific grove california to attend the threeday war resisters league th anniversary conference in august  when the conference ended peck was one of  persons to join a motorcade to fresno in order to challenge the antimass picketing injunction against the ufw which resulted in more than  arrests a week earlier early in the morning on august  peck along with joan baez daniel ellsberg and others picketed near a big ranch without problems pecks group then went to the second vigil at the courthouse where the injunction was debated peck joined  people protesting at union square in nyc on may   for the second annual ufw week which was observed in more than  cities some time prior to the rally ufw singled out gallo wine to boycott along with the continuing boycott of grapes and lettuce and speeches at union square were made by cesar chavez dorothy day and bella abzug on june   peck joined  ufw members in picketing outside the connecticut mutual life insurance company in hartford connecticut the insurance company owned a significant number of citrus fruit groves along the west coast and had stalled previous negotiations for a union contract peck also protested new york citys subway fare increases in the s explaining it unfairly made money off the working class when the subway fare increased from  cents to  cents in  peck walked through the subway gates without paying and encouraged others to do the same he was arrested for this in  and was fined  in  nycs subway fare nearly doubled to  cents and peck joined the first day of protests on september   and walked through the gates without incident and held gates open for other people to walk through without paying he was arrested three times in  for continuing protests against the fare increase fbi court caseedit in  gary thomas rowe jr testified that he was a paid fbi informant in the klan and that on may   the kkk had been given  to  minutes without interference by the police peck filed a lawsuit against the fbi in  seeking  in damages in  he was awarded  and by this time was paralyzed on one side after a stroke peck had been working for amnesty international until his stroke by  peck had moved into a nursing home in minneapolis where he died on july   at age  selected worksedit peck james the ship that never hits port in cantine holly r rainer dachine prison etiquette the convicts compendium of useful information bearsville ny  retort press  reprinted  carbondale  southern illinois university press cf pp – peck james  we who would not kill l stuart  james peck ed  sit ins the students report pdf core  peck james  freedom ride new york simon  schuster oclc   peck james  underdogs vs upperdogs canterbury nh greenleaf books  see alsoedit timeline of the africanamerican civil rights movement referencesedit  a b c d pace eric july   james peck  union organizer who promoted civil rights causes the new york times retrieved april     james peck  washington university film  media archive retrieved august     day samuel h may   remember the nonviolent as well lakeland ledger pp a retrieved april     harris jr robert l terborgpenn rosalyn eds  the columbia guide to african american history since  new york columbia university press p  isbn    prier elmon february   civil rights movement had white heroes too the middletown journal retrieved april     james peck  union organizer who promoted civil rights causes the new york times july     ephron nora critics in the world of the rising souffle new york magazine september    bittman mark the minimalist pudding for purists the new york times december    peck paula the art of fine baking new york  simon and schuster   peck paula art